   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
         <opener><dateline><date when="1914-09-21">Sept. 21, 1914</date></dateline>
            <salute>My Dear<persName key="margaret_anderson">Miss Anderson,</persName></salute></opener>
         <p>I am returning by return mail, with a Special Delivery stamp on it, the proof of my <title key="letterFromLondon" level="a">“London Letter"</title>. I am not sending back the pink proof which, I suppose was the copy you usually keep in the office, as it was hopelessly wrong, a good many lines being left out in the middle. You will find a good many changes in punctuation, and will you please have them printed exactly as they now stand, as punctuation with me is not merely a matter of meaning, but of rhetorical significance. I have appended a footnote in typewriting which you will be so good as to add in whatever type your foot-notes usually appear in.</p>
         <p>You do not say whether you like this “London Letter” or not, and I fear it may not have met with your approval, therefore if so I am very sorry, because I do rather like it.</p>
         </div>
